Send a join request to the running grainfs serve process via its admin UDS.

If the node is already a cluster member the call is a no-op.
If the node is a solo bootstrap and the peer is reachable, the server will
restart and join the cluster on next boot.

Example:
  grainfs join 192.168.1.10:8301 --endpoint /data/admin.sock

Usage:
  grainfs join <peer-raft-addr> [flags]

Flags:
      --endpoint string    admin Unix socket path (required, e.g. ./tmp/admin.sock)
      --force              force join even if solo node has user data (data will be discarded)
  -h, --help               help for join
      --timeout duration   admin command timeout (e.g. 30s, 5m); unset = 30s default; 0 = uncapped (for long follow loops)

Global Flags:
      --log-level string   log level: debug, info, warn, error (default "info")
